	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>A new Brazilian proposal on fisheries subsidies is tabled</h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 November 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> A new proposal tabled by Brazil on November 16th 2005 represents a first attempt to draft a legal text for disciplines on fisheries subsidies. According to the ICTSD, many delegations reacted positively to this proposal, which advocates that disciplines should apply to all subsidies that are ‘given to or on behalf, directly or indirectly, of fishing interests ... Moreover, subsidies granted for the purchase of foreign access rights (government-to-government payments for access by their domestic fleets to foreign EEZ fisheries or to quotas or any other rights established by an RFMO) should also be covered by the definition of fisheries subsidies’.</p><p> Brazil proposes that all subsidies that have a trade- or production-distorting effect should be prohibited. It also advocates a separate ‘S&amp;D box’ of fisheries subsidies to be available only for developing countries. This would permit developing countries to use capacity-enhancing subsidies.</p><p> The EU, voicing strong criticism of the proposal, expressed the view that the proposed legal draft was too long and complex, addressing difficult issues such as flags of convenience, IUU fishing and rules of origin. This complexity would make it difficult for developing countries to comply. It also argued that the stringent rules would run against developing countries' legitimate interests to develop their fishing industries.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p> Disciplines on fisheries subsidies, paper from Brazil, WTO negotiating group on rules, TN/RL/GEN/79, November 16th 2005</p><p>

<a href="http://docsonline.wto.org/DDFDocuments/t/tn/rl/GEN79.doc" target="_self">http://docsonline.wto.org/DDFDocuments/t/tn/rl/GEN79.doc</a> <br /> ICTSD <i> Bridges</i> (weekly) Vol. 9, No. 42, December 7th 2005</p><p>

<a href="http://www.ictsd.org/weekly/05-12-07/story4.htm" target="_self">http://www.ictsd.org/weekly/05-12-07/story4.htm</a> <br /> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> In principle, establishing a separate ‘S&amp;D box’ for fisheries subsidies would be in line with Article 27.1 of the ACSM, which recognises that ‘subsidies may play an important role in economic development’. As such they have a legitimate role to play.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

